along with the process.

00:05:37.190 --> 00:05:40.650
This particular audio sample
that everyone just heard

00:05:40.650 --> 00:05:42.470
comes off of your
album, "Paramount."

00:05:42.470 --> 00:05:43.230
OZARK HENRY: Yes.

00:05:43.230 --> 00:05:46.732
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: Which is the
chicken and the egg question.

00:05:46.732 --> 00:05:47.440
Which came first?

00:05:47.440 --> 00:05:49.570
The idea for the album?

00:05:49.570 --> 00:05:52.910
You were involved with the
National Orchestra of Belgium,

00:05:52.910 --> 00:05:54.980
via invitation.

00:05:54.980 --> 00:05:57.427
How did that cascade into
creating all of this?

00:05:57.427 --> 00:05:59.010
OZARK HENRY: Well,
the thing is that I

00:05:59.010 --> 00:06:02.330
was invited by the National
Orchestra of Belgium

00:06:02.330 --> 00:06:08.070
to curate my work using their
fantastic 90 piece orchestra.

00:06:08.070 --> 00:06:11.730
And knowing that my dad
is a classical composer,

00:06:11.730 --> 00:06:17.390
that's the music and the sound
that I was brought up with.

00:06:17.390 --> 00:06:22.240
For me, it was an opportunity
to really full circle.

00:06:22.240 --> 00:06:25.390
I wanted to explore and
to score every color,

00:06:25.390 --> 00:06:30.020
every dynamic I could get
from such a big orchestra.

00:06:30.020 --> 00:06:34.370
And of course,
being a producer, I

00:06:34.370 --> 00:06:36.980
wanted to record,
record it in a way that

00:06:36.980 --> 00:06:40.510
hasn't been done
before, not thinking

00:06:40.510 --> 00:06:42.190
at that time about
immersive sound,

00:06:42.190 --> 00:06:44.610
because I didn't
even know it existed.

00:06:44.610 --> 00:06:48.040
But I wanted to have
a really big canvas,

00:06:48.040 --> 00:06:54.860
because that is very important
to put a 90 piece orchestra.

00:06:54.860 --> 00:06:57.800
And I wanted to do
something about the space.

00:06:57.800 --> 00:07:00.740
I wanted to share that
special emotion you have

00:07:00.740 --> 00:07:04.860
when being immersed
by that big sound

00:07:04.860 --> 00:07:06.137
when performing with them.

00:07:06.137 --> 00:07:08.470
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: So in
trying to tackle that problem,

00:07:08.470 --> 00:07:10.500
somewhere along the
lines, you began

00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:14.670
to work with the Auro-3D chaps?

00:07:14.670 --> 00:07:17.390
OZARK HENRY: Well,
it was step by step.

00:07:17.390 --> 00:07:19.510
The first thing I had
to question myself

00:07:19.510 --> 00:07:21.370
is, what is the canvas?

00:07:21.370 --> 00:07:23.504
I have some footage too.

00:07:23.504 --> 00:07:25.920
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: Yeah, a
very good way to explain this.

00:07:28.354 --> 00:07:29.770
OZARK HENRY: A
good way to explain

00:07:29.770 --> 00:07:33.640
this is, what is a canvas,
and asking yourself,

00:07:33.640 --> 00:07:36.570
does size matter in music?

00:07:36.570 --> 00:07:38.730
This is Pablo
Picasso's "Guernica,"

00:07:38.730 --> 00:07:42.030
a painting he made
in 1937 expressing

00:07:42.030 --> 00:07:43.860
the horror he witnessed
in events that

00:07:43.860 --> 00:07:46.610
would lead up to World War II.

00:07:46.610 --> 00:07:48.590
People who have had
the opportunity to see

00:07:48.590 --> 00:07:52.710
this in real life, it's huge.

00:07:52.710 --> 00:07:55.010
It's 3 and 1/2 meters high.

00:07:55.010 --> 00:07:58.460
It's almost 8 meters
wide, so it wouldn't even

00:07:58.460 --> 00:08:00.460
never fit in this room.

00:08:00.460 --> 00:08:02.160
Why is it so big?

00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:05.060
Because of what the
content is saying to you.

00:08:05.060 --> 00:08:06.660
it says, there's a war coming.

00:08:06.660 --> 00:08:10.910
It's a monster, and
it's unstoppable.

00:08:10.910 --> 00:08:14.650
I think with music
being an art form,

00:08:14.650 --> 00:08:16.830
as painting is an
art form, one has

00:08:16.830 --> 00:08:18.620
to always question
what canvas will

00:08:18.620 --> 00:08:22.000
I use when starting
a certain work?

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:26.980
I was sure that working with
a 90 piece orchestra having

00:08:26.980 --> 00:08:33.150
the richest instrument
possible in color and dynamic,

00:08:33.150 --> 00:08:36.059
I needed to have a
really big canvas.

00:08:36.059 --> 00:08:38.080
Luckily, I have a big
canvas, the canvas

00:08:38.080 --> 00:08:39.450
that I normally work in.

00:08:39.450 --> 00:08:41.140
And that is my canvas.

00:08:41.140 --> 00:08:43.860
The white circle
represents my canvas.

00:08:43.860 --> 00:08:46.330
The size of the
circle represents

00:08:46.330 --> 00:08:49.010
the quality of my canvas.

00:08:49.010 --> 00:08:52.970
And within that canvas, I have
placed a 90 piece orchestra.

00:08:52.970 --> 00:08:57.300
The size of the pictogram
just represents the quality,

00:08:57.300 --> 00:09:00.650
the dynamic, the direction,
everything such a big orchestra

00:09:00.650 --> 00:09:02.460
has to offer.

00:09:02.460 --> 00:09:04.900
So from my research,
I did understand

00:09:04.900 --> 00:09:08.220
that the good thing is that
my canvas is big enough.

00:09:08.220 --> 00:09:10.700
But I know that
this is not going

00:09:10.700 --> 00:09:16.849
to help me to feel that special
thing, being immersed by sound.

00:09:16.849 --> 00:09:19.390
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: It's like
you can watch a high definition

00:09:19.390 --> 00:09:21.950
film, but you're still on
this side of the screen.

00:09:21.950 --> 00:09:23.908
OZARK HENRY: Yes, you're
always in front of it.

00:09:23.908 --> 00:09:25.270
You're not in the music.

00:09:25.270 --> 00:09:29.960
And of course, knowing
Ronald, and knowing

00:09:29.960 --> 00:09:37.230
that he's the expert in surround
music mixing, engineering,

00:09:37.230 --> 00:09:38.260
recording--

00:09:38.260 --> 00:09:40.170
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: How
early in the process

00:09:40.170 --> 00:09:42.450
did you become involved
in the project?

00:09:42.450 --> 00:09:44.330
RONALD PRENT: Very early.

00:09:44.330 --> 00:09:48.280
I mean, the idea got settled,
and I wanted to do it.

00:09:48.280 --> 00:09:50.090
And Piet called me up.

00:09:50.090 --> 00:09:52.500
Pietr [? Robert ?] came
to visit us, and he said,

00:09:52.500 --> 00:09:53.480
I'm going to do this.

00:09:53.480 --> 00:09:56.200
And he told me what
he just told you guys.

00:09:56.200 --> 00:10:00.630
And I said, oh,
that's a big canvas,

00:10:00.630 --> 00:10:03.994
but there's a new
technology called Auro-3D

00:10:03.994 --> 00:10:06.110
that uses 9 or 10 speakers.

00:10:06.110 --> 00:10:08.630
You can choose
which configuration.

00:10:08.630 --> 00:10:13.290
Which will allow us to
actually represent your canvas

00:10:13.290 --> 00:10:16.790
in a three dimensional
world, and put you

00:10:16.790 --> 00:10:19.760
inside or among the
orchestra, and therefore

00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:22.670
give the listener a completely
different experience

00:10:22.670 --> 00:10:25.170
of your musical ideas.

00:10:25.170 --> 00:10:29.140
And from that moment
on, he said, OK.

00:10:29.140 --> 00:10:31.055
I want to do this.

00:10:31.055 --> 00:10:35.000
So we did the whole
process of the recording,

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:36.300
the mixing, the producing.

00:10:36.300 --> 00:10:38.249
Everything was done
with this in mind.

00:10:38.249 --> 00:10:39.290
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: Cool.

00:10:39.290 --> 00:10:39.790
Cool.

00:10:39.790 --> 00:10:42.770
Even to the point of how
much consideration do

00:10:42.770 --> 00:10:46.250
you have to put where
you're placing a microphone,

00:10:46.250 --> 00:10:47.520
the orientation of that.

00:10:47.520 --> 00:10:51.717
I know we were talking before
about the easy trap of, oh,

00:10:51.717 --> 00:10:53.300
I'll just take a
flute and put it over

00:10:53.300 --> 00:10:55.360
here, and take a clarinet
and put it over there.

00:10:55.360 --> 00:10:57.550
But that doesn't really
serve the purpose.

00:10:57.550 --> 00:10:59.508
RONALD PRENT: It doesn't
serve the purpose, no.

00:10:59.508 --> 00:11:02.167
You want you want to put
the people in a space,

00:11:02.167 --> 00:11:04.000
whether it's virtual
or real doesn't matter.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.910
You want to put them in
a space to experience

00:11:06.910 --> 00:11:09.800
the emotional content of
the music more than just

00:11:09.800 --> 00:11:11.880
with headphones or two speakers.

00:11:11.880 --> 00:11:18.725
And the orchestra is miked in a
traditional way with the Decca

00:11:18.725 --> 00:11:21.460
Tree in a very classical way.

00:11:21.460 --> 00:11:24.030
Then it's miked in
a second way, which

00:11:24.030 --> 00:11:27.870
is more pointed to the
instruments, more pop like.

00:11:27.870 --> 00:11:30.280
And it's done in a
three dimensional way,

00:11:30.280 --> 00:11:31.680
so there's three
different stages

00:11:31.680 --> 00:11:34.360
in which I've recorded
it parallel when

00:11:34.360 --> 00:11:36.130
they did live performances.

00:11:36.130 --> 00:11:38.920
But you also look where do
you record your orchestra?

00:11:38.920 --> 00:11:41.170
Do you do it in the concert
hall, in the studio?

00:11:41.170 --> 00:11:43.320
We ended up doing it
in the rehearsal space

00:11:43.320 --> 00:11:44.230
of the orchestra.

00:11:44.230 --> 00:11:46.440
We went to see the
orchestra before we

00:11:46.440 --> 00:11:48.560
started doing our planning.

00:11:48.560 --> 00:11:51.206
And that was so powerful.

00:11:51.206 --> 00:11:52.580
And I walked around
the orchestra

00:11:52.580 --> 00:11:54.580
while they were rehearsing.

00:11:54.580 --> 00:11:56.242
And I said to Piet,
I said, I don't

00:11:56.242 --> 00:11:58.200
think you have to think
about anything anymore.

00:11:58.200 --> 00:11:59.533
We're going to do in this space.

00:11:59.533 --> 00:12:01.740
I know it's not meant
to be recorded here.

00:12:01.740 --> 00:12:02.970
It's a rehearsal space.

00:12:02.970 --> 00:12:07.050
But the power of the orchestra,
you'll never get it in a studio

00:12:07.050 --> 00:12:11.270
or in a classical
performance space.

00:12:11.270 --> 00:12:13.500
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: And that
seems to make sense too.

00:12:13.500 --> 00:12:16.380
One would think that the
rehearsal space of an orchestra

00:12:16.380 --> 00:12:18.560
is designed in a way to
where they are the ones who

00:12:18.560 --> 00:12:19.620
are hearing it the best.

00:12:19.620 --> 00:12:20.110
RONALD PRENT: Absolutely.

00:12:20.110 --> 00:12:21.210
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
So if you are then

00:12:21.210 --> 00:12:22.793
approaching it to
record it in the way

00:12:22.793 --> 00:12:25.370
that they would hear it,
it's accomplishing the goals

00:12:25.370 --> 00:12:26.850
that you're laying out.

00:12:26.850 --> 00:12:29.620
There's a great documentary
that is available

00:12:29.620 --> 00:12:31.260
online about the
creation of the album,

00:12:31.260 --> 00:12:34.810
and I think we want to
show a snippet of that.

00:12:34.810 --> 00:12:36.790
And the documentary is
also in the surround,

00:12:36.790 --> 00:12:38.530
so you guys will be
able to experience

00:12:38.530 --> 00:12:41.100
a little bit different,
something a little different

00:12:41.100 --> 00:12:43.590
than music.

00:12:43.590 --> 00:12:45.084
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:12:45.084 --> 00:12:47.574
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:13:18.690 --> 00:13:20.060
-[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:15:02.516 --> 00:15:03.460
[END PLAYBACK]

00:15:03.460 --> 00:15:05.251
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
That's a little insight

00:15:05.251 --> 00:15:07.260
into the recording
process and how the way

00:15:07.260 --> 00:15:10.230
it was recorded
lead into the mixing

00:15:10.230 --> 00:15:11.540
and everything like that.

00:15:11.540 --> 00:15:12.610
RONALD PRENT: Yeah.

00:15:12.610 --> 00:15:16.010
If you could hear me speak
Dutch, it's my native language.

00:15:16.010 --> 00:15:18.050
I don't know if
everybody could read it,

00:15:18.050 --> 00:15:19.840
but really quickly,
what I did was

00:15:19.840 --> 00:15:21.840
I used three ways of
recording the orchestra.

00:15:21.840 --> 00:15:24.540
One is the very classical
way, a classical approach

00:15:24.540 --> 00:15:26.780
with Decca Tree in the
front with three microphones

00:15:26.780 --> 00:15:28.620
and some support microphones.

00:15:28.620 --> 00:15:30.460
And the second
way is really pop,

00:15:30.460 --> 00:15:33.820
where each instrument
has its own microphone

00:15:33.820 --> 00:15:35.660
so I can control balance.

00:15:35.660 --> 00:15:39.050
And then the third way
was I put five microphones

00:15:39.050 --> 00:15:41.550
in a square inside
the orchestra.

00:15:41.550 --> 00:15:44.210
And those are projected
in the top loudspeakers

00:15:44.210 --> 00:15:48.060
here, which gave
me the possibility

00:15:48.060 --> 00:15:53.020
to dynamically enhance the
excitement or the arrangement

00:15:53.020 --> 00:15:53.890
of the orchestra.

00:15:53.890 --> 00:15:58.080
There will be parts in songs
that you play where, basically,

00:15:58.080 --> 00:15:59.890
it sounds like a little
chamber orchestra,

00:15:59.890 --> 00:16:01.590
although it's a big orchestra.

00:16:01.590 --> 00:16:03.250
And it's only
either in the front

00:16:03.250 --> 00:16:05.000
or in the bottom
layer of speakers.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:09.090
And when the orchestra really
gets loud and powerful,

00:16:09.090 --> 00:16:12.130
then I add the speakers
as progressive mixing.

00:16:12.130 --> 00:16:13.730
In classical, you
wouldn't do that,

00:16:13.730 --> 00:16:15.230
or you wouldn't be
allowed to do it,

00:16:15.230 --> 00:16:18.380
because it changes the
perspective of the orchestra.

00:16:18.380 --> 00:16:21.450
Here, its use is
an extra dimension

00:16:21.450 --> 00:16:23.350
to the excitement of the music.

00:16:23.350 --> 00:16:26.310
And you can make it small,
and you can make it direct.

00:16:26.310 --> 00:16:29.020
You can make it distant
and very romantic,

00:16:29.020 --> 00:16:32.490
or you can make it
powerfully loud.

00:16:32.490 --> 00:16:37.130
Those were the three
layers that we created.

00:16:37.130 --> 00:16:40.380
Didn't know if it was
going to work before.

00:16:40.380 --> 00:16:44.950
We recorded it that way because
the room would let us do that.

00:16:44.950 --> 00:16:48.090
And then in mixing,
after we did three songs,

00:16:48.090 --> 00:16:50.570
we went in the other
studio in a mastering room,

00:16:50.570 --> 00:16:54.350
and listened to it
on a bigger system.

00:16:54.350 --> 00:16:57.210
And it was really like,
oh, wow, it works.

00:16:57.210 --> 00:17:01.140
That's an exciting
moment, because it really

00:17:01.140 --> 00:17:05.450
gives such a different
dimension to his music.

00:17:05.450 --> 00:17:09.170
OZARK HENRY: This is also
something we have to clear out.

00:17:09.170 --> 00:17:11.849
You were working, and
we couldn't check in 9.1

00:17:11.849 --> 00:17:12.829
while you were working.

00:17:12.829 --> 00:17:14.762
You had to imagine things.

00:17:14.762 --> 00:17:17.000
RONALD PRENT: We were
boyscouting at the time.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:18.800
So you do three processes.

00:17:18.800 --> 00:17:21.410
You do stereo, 5.1 and
9.1 at the same time.

00:17:21.410 --> 00:17:24.339
So you have to choose
what you listen to.

00:17:24.339 --> 00:17:27.184
Because it's not always possible
to listen to all three forms.

00:17:27.184 --> 00:17:28.351
It's switchable.

00:17:28.351 --> 00:17:30.850
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: Difficult
to burn the CD and go play it.

00:17:30.850 --> 00:17:32.433
RONALD PRENT: Yeah,
you can't do that.

00:17:32.433 --> 00:17:36.750
So I choose to work in 5.1 and
not listen to the top speakers.

00:17:36.750 --> 00:17:38.650
And then when I
was finished, I'd

00:17:38.650 --> 00:17:40.410
take the files into
the other studio,

00:17:40.410 --> 00:17:42.474
play it on a real 9.1 set.

00:17:42.474 --> 00:17:43.890
Otherwise, it got
too complicated.

00:17:46.468 --> 00:17:49.200
Now we're a year
further down the line.

00:17:49.200 --> 00:17:52.540
Now there are consoles
developed that can actually

00:17:52.540 --> 00:17:53.790
allow you to do that.

00:17:53.790 --> 00:17:58.370
So, like technology, it
evolves so fast every year.

00:17:58.370 --> 00:18:01.090
Then when we did it, we
couldn't, but now we can.

00:18:01.090 --> 00:18:02.540
And it's only a year later.

00:18:02.540 --> 00:18:03.280
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
You made a touch point

00:18:03.280 --> 00:18:04.650
about the emotional experience.

00:18:04.650 --> 00:18:07.640
And that made me think
about touching on the fact

00:18:07.640 --> 00:18:09.962
that that song that we
heard in the beginning

00:18:09.962 --> 00:18:12.045
might have some emotional
connections because it's

00:18:12.045 --> 00:18:15.480
the recently the late David
Bowie who created that.

00:18:15.480 --> 00:18:17.430
And he works in a
very unique way.

00:18:17.430 --> 00:18:20.902
Not anybody can just go along
and cover a David Bowie song.

00:18:20.902 --> 00:18:22.360
OZARK HENRY: Which
is a good thing.

00:18:22.360 --> 00:18:26.520
I'm a big Bowie fan, so it's
good to have his approval when

00:18:26.520 --> 00:18:28.444
you do a cover version.

00:18:28.444 --> 00:18:30.110
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
How did you approach

00:18:30.110 --> 00:18:34.620
David Bowie to say we have this
idea, we want your blessing?

00:18:34.620 --> 00:18:36.610
And even to the
point where you were

00:18:36.610 --> 00:18:41.010
changing some of the lyrics
and really dismantling

00:18:41.010 --> 00:18:42.320
and recombining them somehow.

00:18:42.320 --> 00:18:44.570
OZARK HENRY: Well, I have a
little history with Bowie.

00:18:44.570 --> 00:18:47.980
When I released my
first album in 1996,

00:18:47.980 --> 00:18:52.430
he spoke out openly that he was
a really big fan of that album.

00:18:52.430 --> 00:18:54.720
I met him later
on at times that I

00:18:54.720 --> 00:18:57.290
wasn't at all successful
with what I was doing.

00:18:57.290 --> 00:19:00.340
And he gave me the
confidence and the courage

00:19:00.340 --> 00:19:03.440
to keep on doing
what I was doing.

00:19:03.440 --> 00:19:07.120
And at the time that I could
do a project like this,

00:19:07.120 --> 00:19:12.200
I made that version of "Heroes,"
which I did send to him,

00:19:12.200 --> 00:19:16.520
explaining that the way
I edited lyrics changed

00:19:16.520 --> 00:19:19.830
the content completely
from what it originally

00:19:19.830 --> 00:19:21.490
was talking about.

00:19:21.490 --> 00:19:25.500
But it was reflecting
this project specifically

00:19:25.500 --> 00:19:29.430
in the sense that a
90 piece orchestra has

00:19:29.430 --> 00:19:32.440
40 different nationalities.

00:19:32.440 --> 00:19:35.030
We were doing
something that I never

00:19:35.030 --> 00:19:37.620
had done before, that was
way bigger than anything

00:19:37.620 --> 00:19:39.870
that I've done before.

00:19:39.870 --> 00:19:42.070
And that meant that I
had to trust everyone.

00:19:42.070 --> 00:19:46.660
And the title of the album
is "Paramount is Harmony.

00:19:46.660 --> 00:19:48.430
Respect Each Individual."

00:19:48.430 --> 00:19:50.700
I think this was possible
because everybody

00:19:50.700 --> 00:19:53.990
was involved in the orchestra.

00:19:53.990 --> 00:19:56.460
Engineering, recording,
everybody in the studio,

00:19:56.460 --> 00:19:58.490
everybody involved,
the people I work with,

00:19:58.490 --> 00:20:02.200
my management-- everybody made
it possible, because we had

00:20:02.200 --> 00:20:05.890
the courage to believe in
something and just go for it,

00:20:05.890 --> 00:20:08.350
even if we didn't have
any blueprint in knowing

00:20:08.350 --> 00:20:09.920
that we would succeed.

00:20:09.920 --> 00:20:12.170
And that's where the song
stands for, I think, the way

00:20:12.170 --> 00:20:13.410
it's been edited.

00:20:13.410 --> 00:20:14.820
And David really liked it.

00:20:14.820 --> 00:20:15.500
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
Yeah I was going

00:20:15.500 --> 00:20:17.200
to ask if he was
able to hear it.

00:20:17.200 --> 00:20:19.970
OZARK HENRY: Yeah, he never
heard it in immersive sound.

00:20:19.970 --> 00:20:24.874
He just heard a stereo demo
that I made, unfortunately.

00:20:24.874 --> 00:20:26.790
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: To
dig a little bit deeper

00:20:26.790 --> 00:20:31.740
into the immersive sound
portion, that's the buzz phrase

00:20:31.740 --> 00:20:34.270
that we're focusing on.

00:20:34.270 --> 00:20:37.620
All of us are
probably old enough

00:20:37.620 --> 00:20:39.650
to have gone through
many iterations now

00:20:39.650 --> 00:20:41.810
of audio technology,
from tapes to CDs

00:20:41.810 --> 00:20:45.060
to the short lived minidisc.

00:20:45.060 --> 00:20:49.520
Does this fall into a technology
in the recording and studio

00:20:49.520 --> 00:20:50.270
world?

00:20:50.270 --> 00:20:54.420
Is it a medium that is going
to be moving to take over?

00:20:54.420 --> 00:20:55.570
Is it a playback device?

00:20:55.570 --> 00:20:58.000
I mean, you have like high
fidelity in the Pono device,

00:20:58.000 --> 00:20:59.830
or FLAC audio files.

00:20:59.830 --> 00:21:03.250
Where does this fit in
that large environment?

00:21:03.250 --> 00:21:06.300
OZARK HENRY: I think, first
of all, it's a technology.

00:21:06.300 --> 00:21:08.680
I mean, it's a medium.

00:21:08.680 --> 00:21:13.850
It allows an artist to
have a way bigger canvas,

00:21:13.850 --> 00:21:15.470
actually, the canvas
one would always

00:21:15.470 --> 00:21:19.780
dream of, to express everything
that is possible with music.

00:21:19.780 --> 00:21:23.030
This is, I think, beyond styles.

00:21:23.030 --> 00:21:25.240
This is even probably
beyond music.

00:21:25.240 --> 00:21:27.140
I think it can express
way more, because it

00:21:27.140 --> 00:21:29.690
is the natural way of
listening to things,

00:21:29.690 --> 00:21:35.670
the way we experience
sound day to day.

00:21:35.670 --> 00:21:39.470
And it gives back
what has been lost,

00:21:39.470 --> 00:21:42.470
I think, throughout the
technology and the way

00:21:42.470 --> 00:21:44.670
it's been commercialized.

00:21:44.670 --> 00:21:47.430
That is, the original work.

00:21:47.430 --> 00:21:56.660
And to explain, going
back to the Picasso,

00:21:56.660 --> 00:22:00.580
if that were a piece
of music, and you

00:22:00.580 --> 00:22:03.890
were to see the original
work, and it would be a song,

00:22:03.890 --> 00:22:05.697
and it comes out as a
piece of music today,

00:22:05.697 --> 00:22:08.030
and you would be interested
in it, and you would buy it,

00:22:08.030 --> 00:22:10.590
you would download it,
or you would stream it.

00:22:10.590 --> 00:22:13.090
Then you would have this.

00:22:13.090 --> 00:22:15.230
So imagine you're
Pablo Picasso, and you

00:22:15.230 --> 00:22:19.860
want to express like the
horror leading to events

00:22:19.860 --> 00:22:22.250
that will start a World War.

00:22:22.250 --> 00:22:24.510
This is hardly noticeable.

00:22:24.510 --> 00:22:27.370
I think it's paying no
respect or no tribute

00:22:27.370 --> 00:22:30.470
to what an artist had intended.

00:22:30.470 --> 00:22:33.100
And I think an MP3
is a great thing,

00:22:33.100 --> 00:22:36.720
because it allows you to
carry music with you on a very

00:22:36.720 --> 00:22:38.620
small device.

00:22:38.620 --> 00:22:43.720
But is that the purpose of the
one who is making the music?

00:22:43.720 --> 00:22:45.740
Is that the purpose
of the artist?

00:22:45.740 --> 00:22:48.780
Making something that you can
put in a really small device?

00:22:51.054 --> 00:22:52.470
And then, of course,
there's a lot

00:22:52.470 --> 00:22:55.010
of people criticizing
the way I presented,

00:22:55.010 --> 00:22:56.310
saying but it's music.

00:22:56.310 --> 00:22:58.080
You can zoom into it.

00:22:58.080 --> 00:23:00.830
But if you zoom into it,
of course, it's deformed.

00:23:03.780 --> 00:23:05.650
Going back to what
I said before,

00:23:05.650 --> 00:23:08.760
it's all about respecting
the original work.

00:23:08.760 --> 00:23:12.900
My interest as an artist
is using technologies

00:23:12.900 --> 00:23:16.090
that allow me to offer
an experience which

00:23:16.090 --> 00:23:19.620
is way beyond anything
that one can offer now,

00:23:19.620 --> 00:23:21.000
but also to share it.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:23.300
Because I think the biggest
challenge, after all,

00:23:23.300 --> 00:23:29.640
was for us not to make this
album using immersive sound,

00:23:29.640 --> 00:23:32.340
but the hardest thing is
just to communicate it

00:23:32.340 --> 00:23:34.960
and to get it
towards an audience.

00:23:34.960 --> 00:23:39.250
Although it's quite easy to
do, because these sound files

00:23:39.250 --> 00:23:41.570
may have been big
files some time ago,

00:23:41.570 --> 00:23:43.010
but they're not today.

00:23:43.010 --> 00:23:47.657
If you can stream a film, then
for sure, you can stream this.

00:23:47.657 --> 00:23:49.240
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
Well, maybe that's

00:23:49.240 --> 00:23:51.490
a bigger question about
technology, to back up.

00:23:51.490 --> 00:23:54.550
Because it's clear.

00:23:54.550 --> 00:23:56.350
Everyone here probably
has a smartphone

00:23:56.350 --> 00:24:00.720
in their pocket with catalogs
upon catalogs of music.

00:24:00.720 --> 00:24:02.770
OZARK HENRY: Even I do.

00:24:02.770 --> 00:24:04.050
And I think it's great.

00:24:04.050 --> 00:24:05.466
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
How do you get

00:24:05.466 --> 00:24:08.460
around the ubiquity of that,
though, to present them?

00:24:08.460 --> 00:24:11.560
How do you first explain
even what they're missing,

00:24:11.560 --> 00:24:16.260
and then also translate this
experience to those devices?

00:24:16.260 --> 00:24:19.489
I mean, it's easy for us to set
up here with this great speaker

00:24:19.489 --> 00:24:21.155
system that these
guys have put in here,

00:24:21.155 --> 00:24:22.988
but obviously you can't
walk down the street

00:24:22.988 --> 00:24:25.170
with this rig around you.

00:24:25.170 --> 00:24:27.570
How do you get
that to the pocket?

00:24:27.570 --> 00:24:30.287
OZARK HENRY: Well, the thing is
that for now it's just trying

00:24:30.287 --> 00:24:31.370
to communicate what it is.

00:24:31.370 --> 00:24:35.500
The only way to do it
is to experience it.

00:24:35.500 --> 00:24:37.930
RONALD PRENT: But
there are developments

00:24:37.930 --> 00:24:39.340
in the new technology.

00:24:39.340 --> 00:24:42.510
For now, we use a pure
audio Blu-ray technology

00:24:42.510 --> 00:24:46.980
to be able to play it with
or without video in 9.1.

00:24:46.980 --> 00:24:50.250
But sooner, it also will
be possible to stream

00:24:50.250 --> 00:24:52.210
this in 9.1 lossless.

00:24:52.210 --> 00:24:56.330
And in late spring,
on Android devices

00:24:56.330 --> 00:25:00.810
we'll be able to play back
from Android devices in 9.1

00:25:00.810 --> 00:25:01.800
and stream it.

00:25:01.800 --> 00:25:04.258
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: And we have
some of the representatives

00:25:04.258 --> 00:25:05.067
from Auro-3D here.

00:25:05.067 --> 00:25:06.900
They were the ones who
brought in the system

00:25:06.900 --> 00:25:08.276
and set it all up.

00:25:08.276 --> 00:25:09.650
And in our
conversations, they've

00:25:09.650 --> 00:25:12.560
mentioned things like, yes,
we have these big playback

00:25:12.560 --> 00:25:18.070
systems that can do the 9.1
set up, or even larger set ups,

00:25:18.070 --> 00:25:22.786
but also encoders that work in
stereo left and right for that.

00:25:22.786 --> 00:25:25.160
So you don't have to go out
and retrofit your entire home

00:25:25.160 --> 00:25:27.237
theater system to
be able to reap

00:25:27.237 --> 00:25:28.570
the benefits of this technology.

00:25:28.570 --> 00:25:29.260
So that's great.

00:25:31.830 --> 00:25:35.470
We've seen game changers before.

00:25:35.470 --> 00:25:39.040
The CD changed the
musical landscape.

00:25:39.040 --> 00:25:41.260
And then we've also seen
failed game changers,

00:25:41.260 --> 00:25:43.189
like who has a minidisc player?

00:25:43.189 --> 00:25:44.730
I actually do have
a minidisc player.

00:25:44.730 --> 00:25:46.367
OZARK HENRY: Yeah, me too.

00:25:46.367 --> 00:25:48.200
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
It's a great technology,

00:25:48.200 --> 00:25:50.091
but it didn't stick.

00:25:50.091 --> 00:25:51.634
And you said you
were doing this.

00:25:51.634 --> 00:25:53.425
We're working toward
the streaming element,

00:25:53.425 --> 00:25:56.720
but right now it's Blu-ray.

00:25:56.720 --> 00:25:58.820
What if it turns out that
Blu-ray doesn't stick?

00:25:58.820 --> 00:26:00.840
OZARK HENRY: But I think
the Blu-ray doesn't.

00:26:00.840 --> 00:26:04.440
Everything will become you can
stream it, you can download it.

00:26:04.440 --> 00:26:08.680
I think the idea to put all your
effort in a carrier is weird.

00:26:08.680 --> 00:26:11.820
It's like having a phone
with a bad receiver.

00:26:11.820 --> 00:26:14.610
And the only effort you do is
to make it smaller and smaller

00:26:14.610 --> 00:26:18.030
instead of working
on a better receiver.

00:26:18.030 --> 00:26:20.000
I think the technology
is out there.

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:23.420
You can make this wonderful.

00:26:23.420 --> 00:26:27.680
You have a great canvas
to make wonderful music.

00:26:27.680 --> 00:26:29.810
And if the platforms make
it available, which is,

00:26:29.810 --> 00:26:36.890
I think, just saying a yes
or a go, then there we are.

00:26:36.890 --> 00:26:40.430
And then of course, you have the
choice to build up your system.

00:26:40.430 --> 00:26:44.010
There's a lot of people
already having a 5.1 system.

00:26:44.010 --> 00:26:45.630
When making this
album, of course,

00:26:45.630 --> 00:26:50.110
we started-- because it was our
dream to have the 9.1 set up.

00:26:50.110 --> 00:26:53.960
And then Ronald made
versions in 5.1 and stereo.

00:26:53.960 --> 00:26:55.240
So you can downsize.

00:26:55.240 --> 00:26:59.840
And of course, we also have
an MP3 version of this album.

00:26:59.840 --> 00:27:04.220
So it's out there
in many formats.

00:27:04.220 --> 00:27:07.380
The question is not what
could be the best carrier

00:27:07.380 --> 00:27:09.010
to hold all those formats.

00:27:09.010 --> 00:27:10.510
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
That seems to be

00:27:10.510 --> 00:27:13.620
a common thread across
many artistic media lately,

00:27:13.620 --> 00:27:16.990
is getting away from the
sticking point of the medium,

00:27:16.990 --> 00:27:19.220
and finding a way to get
back to the actual creation,

00:27:19.220 --> 00:27:20.607
the actual experience.

00:27:20.607 --> 00:27:22.690
RONALD PRENT: And up the
quality for the listener.

00:27:25.770 --> 00:27:27.820
Bigger canvas.

00:27:27.820 --> 00:27:30.500
OZARK HENRY: I think if
we would talk about wine,

00:27:30.500 --> 00:27:32.277
we would never have
this discussion.

00:27:32.277 --> 00:27:33.860
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
It wouldn't matter

00:27:33.860 --> 00:27:35.139
what bottle it would come in.

00:27:35.139 --> 00:27:36.180
You'd focus on the taste.

00:27:36.180 --> 00:27:37.638
OZARK HENRY: No,
I mean if we would

00:27:37.638 --> 00:27:40.290
downsize the quality that much.

00:27:40.290 --> 00:27:45.050
I'm a wine lover, so for
me, this makes sense.

00:27:45.050 --> 00:27:47.510
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: You
touched on the home theater

00:27:47.510 --> 00:27:50.090
applications, which, of
course, you think 5.1 surround,

00:27:50.090 --> 00:27:52.365
you think home theater or
movie theater applications.

00:27:52.365 --> 00:27:55.910
so that's film and now music,
and being able to present

00:27:55.910 --> 00:27:58.070
it that way, but there's more.

00:27:58.070 --> 00:28:00.964
You were talking about
maybe sports applications

00:28:00.964 --> 00:28:01.630
in various ways.

00:28:01.630 --> 00:28:05.650
And then your great
upcoming project as well.

00:28:05.650 --> 00:28:08.420
OZARK HENRY: Yeah, well
I'm a goodwill ambassador

00:28:08.420 --> 00:28:12.400
in the fight against
human trafficking.

00:28:12.400 --> 00:28:16.190
And I want to make an
immersive sound experience that

00:28:16.190 --> 00:28:18.950
can travel from music festival
to music festival that

00:28:18.950 --> 00:28:20.950
gives people an
experience of like three

00:28:20.950 --> 00:28:24.980
minutes, an experience
of how it feels

00:28:24.980 --> 00:28:28.460
to have your identity taken
away and to have control

00:28:28.460 --> 00:28:31.030
of your life taken away.

00:28:31.030 --> 00:28:31.600
Why?

00:28:31.600 --> 00:28:33.224
Because a lot of
people don't know what

00:28:33.224 --> 00:28:35.480
human trafficking is about.

00:28:35.480 --> 00:28:36.980
They don't know
what it stands for,

00:28:36.980 --> 00:28:43.380
and therefore they don't
recognize when it happens.

00:28:43.380 --> 00:28:46.160
That's also the case
mainly for victims.

00:28:46.160 --> 00:28:49.140
They don't realize that they are
victims of human trafficking.

00:28:49.140 --> 00:28:53.060
And if you realize that
human trafficking is

00:28:53.060 --> 00:29:01.700
as lucrative as the whole
industry around drugs or arms,

00:29:01.700 --> 00:29:03.450
then you know it's a
big thing in itself,

00:29:03.450 --> 00:29:06.250
and it's something we have
to do something about it.

00:29:06.250 --> 00:29:08.250
It shames us all, and
every country in the world

00:29:08.250 --> 00:29:10.070
is affected by it.

00:29:10.070 --> 00:29:13.950
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: Even
just discussing it before,

00:29:13.950 --> 00:29:18.290
the idea, the concept of being
inside of a shipping container

00:29:18.290 --> 00:29:22.220
and being exposed to the
sound experiences in a three

00:29:22.220 --> 00:29:26.050
dimensional way, it
gives me anxiety.

00:29:26.050 --> 00:29:27.730
It makes me feel
uncomfortable even

00:29:27.730 --> 00:29:28.990
thinking about the concept.

00:29:28.990 --> 00:29:33.160
So I hope that you can find what
you need to fully realize that.

00:29:33.160 --> 00:29:35.001
And I hope that in the
future we can find--

00:29:35.001 --> 00:29:37.250
OZARK HENRY: Yeah, and I
hope it will have its effect,

00:29:37.250 --> 00:29:41.690
and that people think about
it and realize that it's not

00:29:41.690 --> 00:29:44.932
as invisible as we think.

00:29:44.932 --> 00:29:47.390
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT: Have you
done a lot of-- and maybe this

00:29:47.390 --> 00:29:50.200
is actually a question
better for you in the studio

00:29:50.200 --> 00:29:52.470
environment, a lot of
discussion with this technology

00:29:52.470 --> 00:29:53.928
and with this
approach to recording

00:29:53.928 --> 00:29:55.290
music with other artists?

00:29:55.290 --> 00:29:57.650
And what sort of
feedback are you

00:29:57.650 --> 00:30:00.450
getting from other musicians?

00:30:00.450 --> 00:30:05.810
RONALD PRENT: We've done not
recording a project like Piet's

00:30:05.810 --> 00:30:07.830
from the beginning,
but at the moment,

00:30:07.830 --> 00:30:11.240
we also do a lot of
back catalog when

00:30:11.240 --> 00:30:13.590
there's interesting material.

00:30:13.590 --> 00:30:17.710
We did Tiesto "Elements
of Life" album.

00:30:17.710 --> 00:30:19.550
That's 10 years old this year.

00:30:19.550 --> 00:30:23.330
We did "Dead" in 9.1, which
is original dance music.

00:30:23.330 --> 00:30:26.310
And it's amazing that stuff
that's done 10 years ago,

00:30:26.310 --> 00:30:29.620
and you get only the
way they work in steps--

00:30:29.620 --> 00:30:31.370
in groups of instruments.

00:30:31.370 --> 00:30:35.600
Like you could still do
with immersive sound to make

00:30:35.600 --> 00:30:37.350
a different experience
in the dance.

00:30:37.350 --> 00:30:40.430
And I've just recently
done a project

00:30:40.430 --> 00:30:44.360
with a guy called [? Press. ?]
He's a DJ out of London,

00:30:44.360 --> 00:30:45.970
and that's EDM music.

00:30:45.970 --> 00:30:49.790
And that's a brand new album
that comes out in two months.

00:30:49.790 --> 00:30:52.370
And we've done a
9.1 version of it.

00:30:52.370 --> 00:30:55.670
And it's for them, it's drugs.

00:30:55.670 --> 00:30:57.260
I did three tracks for tryout.

00:30:57.260 --> 00:30:57.760
He came.

00:30:57.760 --> 00:30:58.670
He sat there.

00:30:58.670 --> 00:31:01.610
He sat the whole day and
listened to these three tracks

00:31:01.610 --> 00:31:03.570
and went out of his mind.

00:31:03.570 --> 00:31:04.860
He said, this is possible?

00:31:04.860 --> 00:31:05.360
I said, yes.

00:31:05.360 --> 00:31:08.050
This is possible
with all your music.

00:31:08.050 --> 00:31:13.880
And then the other eight tracks
that I had to mix got remixed.

00:31:13.880 --> 00:31:17.050
He went back to London,
and I got new versions.

00:31:17.050 --> 00:31:19.110
Because he knew
what was possible.

00:31:19.110 --> 00:31:21.260
He went along, and
because for them it's

00:31:21.260 --> 00:31:25.545
a permanent creative process
of creating and then mixing,

00:31:25.545 --> 00:31:28.220
it's very close together.

00:31:28.220 --> 00:31:31.430
And in 9.1, that's a bit
more difficult, that process

00:31:31.430 --> 00:31:32.360
for him.

00:31:32.360 --> 00:31:35.160
Because he cannot change
everything every 10 seconds.

00:31:35.160 --> 00:31:39.080
But they do, and they come
up with great ideas what

00:31:39.080 --> 00:31:42.580
to do with beats and how to use
the speakers in an arrangement.

00:31:42.580 --> 00:31:44.820
To not put something in
the top, because it's

00:31:44.820 --> 00:31:45.720
nice to put it there.

00:31:45.720 --> 00:31:49.790
It's because it has a function
in music, and even in EDM.

00:31:49.790 --> 00:31:54.440
I tell you, it's not what I play
at home, but it's great to mix.

00:31:54.440 --> 00:31:59.250
It's really fun to be in,
because there's no limitations.

00:31:59.250 --> 00:32:02.210
You have this big space, where
you can put all kinds of sounds

00:32:02.210 --> 00:32:06.400
in and create a vibe
for five minutes.

00:32:06.400 --> 00:32:11.120
And so you see that when you
bring artists into that process

00:32:11.120 --> 00:32:15.180
early or even later, they start
rethinking their whole-- oh,

00:32:15.180 --> 00:32:16.020
now I can do this.

00:32:16.020 --> 00:32:16.680
Now I can do this.

00:32:16.680 --> 00:32:17.971
Now I can have this excitement.

00:32:17.971 --> 00:32:20.970
Now I can have this dark mood.

00:32:20.970 --> 00:32:24.460
And it's much easier
for them to produce it,

00:32:24.460 --> 00:32:27.880
because in stereo you have this
little, small window that you

00:32:27.880 --> 00:32:30.710
have to look through, and have
to cramp everything in there,

00:32:30.710 --> 00:32:32.670
and they want
everything in there.

00:32:32.670 --> 00:32:36.820
So it sometimes
becomes a flat thing

00:32:36.820 --> 00:32:40.230
that we then make loud so
everybody thinks it's exciting.

00:32:40.230 --> 00:32:45.140
Whereas if you give
them this whole space,

00:32:45.140 --> 00:32:46.370
it doesn't have to be loud.

00:32:46.370 --> 00:32:49.540
Because it's loud because
of the space that there is.

00:32:49.540 --> 00:32:51.190
So you don't need
all the processing

00:32:51.190 --> 00:32:54.980
that we now in today's
world use to make everything

00:32:54.980 --> 00:32:58.500
brutally loud so they
think we listen to it.

00:32:58.500 --> 00:32:59.640
And it's really this small.

00:32:59.640 --> 00:33:01.160
It's like his canvas.

00:33:01.160 --> 00:33:03.147
It's a small window
that you look through.

