RONALD PRENT: At the moment.

00:44:00.220 --> 00:44:01.851
MATTHEW HENDERSHOT:
Please, go ahead.

00:44:01.851 --> 00:44:03.140
AUDIENCE: I think you might
have just answered my question,

00:44:03.140 --> 00:44:05.020
but I was going to
ask how you chose

00:44:05.020 --> 00:44:08.440
9.1 when it seems
like adding more

00:44:08.440 --> 00:44:12.220
and more speakers in
an ever denser array

00:44:12.220 --> 00:44:14.321
would just be even better.

00:44:14.321 --> 00:44:15.820
RONALD PRENT: But
more speakers also

00:44:15.820 --> 00:44:20.800
can give more problems in
timing between the speakers.

00:44:20.800 --> 00:44:23.460
5.1 is an established
format, and the added four

00:44:23.460 --> 00:44:28.870
high speakers or the 5 if you
